1. If you try to convert the cycle count data to tidy format, what is one obstacle you will encounter?

When trying to collate the data from the three years provided, I found that the the data collection each year was carried out without regard for the previous years and many locations were assigned slightly different names by the presumably different parties who gathered the data. Some locations, notable the Vector/Spark Arena, were also renamed during this period and the data was not updated to reflect this.

In essence, the obstacle is inconsistency in data collection.

2. Compute the total number of cyclists counted for each day, and a suitable summary of the rainfall for each day, in the same data frame.

Reading the cyclists data into a single data frame for processing

# Reading in data
setwd("C:/Users/jimzh/OneDrive - The University of Auckland/Documents/2021/Sem2/STATS369/369Ass1")
bike_files <- list.files(pattern="^daily",full=TRUE)
bike_data <- map(bike_files,read_csv)

allbikes <- bind_rows(bike_tidy) %>% drop_na()

# Tidying dates and summing riders per day across all locations.
allbikes$tidy_date <- as.Date(allbikes$Date,"%a %d %b %Y" )
citysummary <- aggregate(allbikes["rider_count"], by=allbikes["tidy_date"], sum)

Processing and attaching rainfall (modified to .csv). I made the assumption that the rainfall for each day was the average of the rainfalls in the north and the south, and created a new dataframe which columns for date, total cyclists counted, average rainfall.

# Reading in data
rain_files <- list.files(pattern="^rain",full=TRUE)
rainfall1  <- rain_files[1] %>% read_csv(skip = 9)
rainfall2  <- rain_files[2] %>% read_csv(skip = 9)
rainfalldata <- bind_rows(rainfall1,rainfall2) %>% drop_na()
# Rename to avoid parentheses causing errors when passed as input
names(rainfalldata)[2] <- "Date"
names(rainfalldata)[3] <- "Time"
names(rainfalldata)[4] <- "Amount"


# Tidying date
rainfalldata$tidy_date <- as.Date(as.character(rainfalldata$Date), format = "%Y%m%d")
rainfalldata <- group_by(rainfalldata, Station) 

# Splitting data by station measured at and creating summary 'rainfall' variable as the average of the two stations.
northdaily <- rainfalldata %>% subset(rainfalldata$Station == 22719) 
northrainsum <- aggregate(northdaily["Amount"], by=northdaily["tidy_date"],sum)
southdaily <- rainfalldata %>% subset(rainfalldata$Station == 37852) 
southrainsum <- aggregate(southdaily["Amount"], by=southdaily["tidy_date"],sum)
southrainsum <- southrainsum[-nrow(southrainsum),]

citysummary$rainfall <- (0.5 * (northrainsum$Amount + southrainsum$Amount))

3. Draw suitable graphs to display how the number of cyclists varies over time, over season, over day of the week, and with rain.

Graph of total counted cyclists over time, colored by rainfall:

ggplot(citysummary, 
       aes(x = tidy_date, 
           y = rider_count, 
           color = rainfall, size = rainfall)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .6) +
  labs(title = "Daily rider count over time, colored + sized by rainfall") + scale_color_gradient(low="blue", high="red")  + scale_size(guide = 'none') + xlab("Date") + ylab("Riders counted")

Generating Season and Weekday variables.

# Finding weekday and week number (counting from 01-01-2016)
citysummary$weekday <- weekdays(citysummary$tidy_date)
citysummary <- citysummary %>% mutate(week = (year(tidy_date) - year(min(tidy_date)))*52 + week(tidy_date) - week(min(tidy_date)))

# Grouping and plotting summary
citysummary$weekday <- factor(citysummary$weekday, levels = c("Monday","Tuesday","Wednesday","Thursday","Friday","Saturday","Sunday"))
ggplot(citysummary)+geom_boxplot(aes(x=weekday, y = rider_count, color = weekday)) +  theme(legend.position="none") + xlab("Weekday") + ylab("Riders counted")

Data visualized in time series by riders per week rather than day, for easier viewing (colored by mean rain for the week). Since the data appeared relatively consistent and weekday should be independent of rain, I took the average of all the days in each week and plotted that as a single object to cut down on noise in the graph.

# Aggregating rainfall and riders found in each week and joining into a new dataframe.
citysummaryweek <- left_join(aggregate(citysummary["rider_count"], by = citysummary["week"],mean), aggregate(citysummary["rainfall"], by = citysummary["week"],mean))
## Joining, by = "week"
# Finding seasons using modular arithmatic and intervals of weeks.
citysummaryweek$date = as.Date("2016-01-01") + 7*citysummaryweek$week
citysummaryweek$season <- ifelse((citysummaryweek$week %% 52 >= 23 & citysummaryweek$week %% 52 <=35), "Winter","Not")
citysummaryweek$season <- ifelse((citysummaryweek$week %% 52 >= 36 & citysummaryweek$week %% 52 <=48), "Spring",citysummaryweek$season)
citysummaryweek$season <- ifelse((citysummaryweek$week %% 52 >= 10 & citysummaryweek$week %% 52 <=22), "Autumn",citysummaryweek$season)
citysummaryweek$season <- ifelse(citysummaryweek$season == "Not", "Summer",citysummaryweek$season)
citysummaryweek$season = factor(citysummaryweek$season,levels=c("Summer","Autumn","Winter","Spring"))


ggplot(citysummaryweek, 
       aes(x = date, 
           y = rider_count, 
           color = rainfall, size = rainfall)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .6) +
  labs(title = "Riders between 2016-2018, weekly avg, colored + sized by rainfall") + scale_color_gradient(low="blue", high="red")  + scale_size(guide = 'none') + xlab("Week beginning ~") + ylab("Daily average riders") + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60))

And data colored by season instead of rainfall:

ggplot(citysummaryweek, 
       aes(x = date, 
           y = rider_count, 
           color = season, size = rainfall)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .6) +
  labs(title = "Riders between 2016-2018, weekly avg, colored by season") + scale_size(guide = 'none') + xlab("Week beginning in ~") + ylab("Daily average riders") + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60))

We see that as winter nears, fewer and fewer people tend to cycle in Auckland every week. In spring and as it warms, the number of people counted tends to rise again. Number of cyclists counted over the course of a week tended to increase from a minimum on Saturday to a maximum on Tuesday, and fall again. Weeks with higher average rainfall also tend to have lower average daily riders, which can be seen most clearly from the scatter plot of all 1096 days, where we notice large/brighter dots clearly falling further down the Y axis on average.

Overall, there appears to be an increasing trend over the last 3 years of more and more cyclists counted each year, perhaps owing to population growth or population density increase.

4. Fit a regression model to predict the number of cyclist from year, season, day of the week, and rain.

# Applying the seasons chategories to the citysummary data frame
citysummary$season <- ifelse((citysummary$week %% 52 >= 23 & citysummary$week %% 52 <=35), "Winter","Not")
citysummary$season <- ifelse((citysummary$week %% 52 >= 36 & citysummary$week %% 52 <=48), "Spring",citysummary$season)
citysummary$season <- ifelse((citysummary$week %% 52 >= 10 & citysummary$week %% 52 <=22), "Autumn",citysummary$season)
citysummary$season <- ifelse(citysummary$season == "Not", "Summer",citysummary$season)
citysummary$season = factor(citysummary$season,levels=c("Summer","Autumn","Winter","Spring"))

We now have a single data frame containing amount of rain, date, day of the week, season, and the number of riders counted. First checking for interaction:

# With results = 'hide' to save the document from a page of coefficients
riders_i.lm = lm(rider_count ~ rainfall * weekday * season * tidy_date, data = citysummary)
summary(riders_i.lm)

We find that there is not enough significant evidence that there is interaction between the variables rainfall, weekday, season and time.

Fitting the simple additive model:

riders.lm = lm(rider_count ~ rainfall + weekday + season + tidy_date, data = citysummary)
summary(riders.lm)

All terms are significant at a 10% threshold. We visually test the impact of rain by plotting two years, one with the rain removed.

# New test summary with all rainfalls set to zero
citysummary_norain <- citysummary[-3]
citysummary_norain$rainfall <- 0

# Replacing rider count with predicted count from the model
citysummary_norain$predicted_riders <- predict(riders.lm, newdata = citysummary_norain[c("tidy_date","rainfall","weekday","season")])
citysummary$predicted_riders <- predict(riders.lm, newdata = citysummary[c("tidy_date","rainfall","weekday","season")])

# Plot real data
ggplot(citysummary, 
       aes(x = tidy_date, 
           y = rider_count)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .6) +
  labs(title = "Predicted Daily riders between 2016-2018 using real rain data") + xlab("Date") + ylab("Riders counted") + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60)) + ylim(0,20000) + geom_point(color = "darkorchid4") 

# Plot prediction with rain
ggplot(citysummary, 
       aes(x = tidy_date, 
           y = predicted_riders)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .6) +
  labs(title = "Predicted Daily riders between 2016-2018 using real rain data") + xlab("Date") + ylab("Riders counted") + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60)) + ylim(0,20000) + geom_point(color = "darkorchid4") 

# Plot prediction with rain removed
ggplot(citysummary_norain, 
       aes(x = tidy_date, 
           y = predicted_riders)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .6) +
  labs(title = "Predicted daily riders between 2016-2018 if rainfall = 0") + scale_color_gradient(low="blue", high="red")  + scale_size(guide = 'none') + xlab("Date") + ylab("Riders counted") + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60)) + ylim(0,20000)

Visually, we can see that the graph of predicted daily riders is a decent match for the trend in the real data, although it doesn’t recreate the level of scatter/unpredictability of the real world (as expected).

Comparing the graphs of predicted riders (with real rain) and predicted riders (with no rain), we can very clearly see the effect that rain has on the riders counted in Auckland. This is backed up by the P-value of the rainfall coefficient of the linear model, which is well below any reasonable confidence threshold.

5. Based on your graphs and model, does rain have a big impact on the number of people cycling in Auckland?

Based on these graphs and the linear model, I therefore conclude that the rain does have an impact on the number of people cycling in Auckland, although not the largest/most significant impact out of the variables given.
